# Function composition

In [mathematics](/Mathematics), **function composition** is an operation that takes two [functions](/Function_(mathematics)) \( f \) and \( g \) and produces a function \( h \) such that \( h(x) = g(f(x)) \). In this operation, the function \( g \) is applied to the result of applying the function \( f \) to \( x \). That is, the functions \( f \colon X \to Y \) and \( g \colon Y \to Z \) are composed to yield a function that maps \( x \) in \( X \) to \( g(f(x)) \) in \( Z \).

Intuitively, if \( z \) is a function of \( y \), and \( y \) is a function of \( x \), then \( z \) is a function of \( x \). The resulting composite function is denoted \( g \circ f \colon X \to Z \), defined by \( (g \circ f)(x) = g(f(x)) \) for all \( x \) in \( X \). The notation \( g \circ f \) is read as "\( g \) circle \( f \)", "\( g \) composed with \( f \)", "\( g \) after \( f \)", or "\( g \) of \( f \)".

The composition of functions is a special case of the composition of [relations](/Relation_(mathematics)), sometimes also called [composition of maps](/Function_(mathematics)). As a result, all properties of the composition of relations are true of composition of functions, such as the property of [associativity](/Associative_property). The composition of functions is also a special case of [composition of binary relations](/Composition_of_relations), which is defined for [binary relations](/Binary_relation) in general.

## Definition

Given two functions \( f \colon X \to Y \) and \( g \colon Y \to Z \), the composite function \( g \circ f \colon X \to Z \) is defined by

\[
(g \circ f)(x) = g(f(x))
\]

for all \( x \) in \( X \).

In other words, the composition \( g \circ f \) is the function that first applies \( f \) to an argument \( x \), and then applies \( g \) to the result. Note that the composition \( g \circ f \) is only defined if the [codomain](/Codomain) of \( f \) is the [domain](/Domain_of_a_function) of \( g \). More generally, it is sufficient that the [image](/Image_(mathematics)) of \( f \) is contained in the domain of \( g \).

The order of composition is important. In general, \( g \circ f \) is not the same as \( f \circ g \). For example, if \( f \) is a function from the [real numbers](/Real_number) to the [positive real numbers](/Positive_real_numbers) defined by \( f(x) = x^2 \), and \( g \) is a function from the positive real numbers to the real numbers defined by \( g(x) = \sqrt{x} \), then \( g \circ f \) is the function from the real numbers to the real numbers defined by \( (g \circ f)(x) = \sqrt{x^2} = |x| \), while \( f \circ g \) is the function from the positive real numbers to the positive real numbers defined by \( (f \circ g)(x) = (\sqrt{x})^2 = x \).

## Properties

The composition of functions is [associative](/Associative_property). That is, if \( f \), \( g \), and \( h \) are functions with suitably chosen domains and codomains, then

\[
(h \circ g) \circ f = h \circ (g \circ f)
\]

This means that the parentheses can be omitted without ambiguity, and the composition can be written as \( h \circ g \circ f \).

The composition of functions is not [commutative](/Commutative_property). That is, in general, \( g \circ f \) is not the same as \( f \circ g \). For example, if \( f \) and \( g \) are the functions defined above, then \( g \circ f \) is the [absolute value](/Absolute_value) function, while \( f \circ g \) is the identity function on the positive real numbers.

The composition of functions is [distributive](/Distributive_property) over [function addition](/Function_addition). That is, if \( f \), \( g \), and \( h \) are functions with suitably chosen domains and codomains, then

\[
f \circ (g + h) = f \circ g + f \circ h
\]

and

\[
(g + h) \circ f = g \circ f + h \circ f
\]

The composition of functions is also compatible with [scalar multiplication](/Scalar_multiplication). That is, if \( f \) and \( g \) are functions with suitably chosen domains and codomains, and \( c \) is a scalar, then

\[
f \circ (c g) = c (f \circ g)
\]

and

\[
(c f) \circ g = c (f \circ g)
\]

## Functional powers

If \( Y \subseteq X \), then \( f \) may compose with itself, and this is sometimes denoted as \( f^2 \). Thus:

\[
f^2(x) = f(f(x))
\]

and

\[
f^n(x) = f(f^{n-1}(x))
\]

for all \( n \) in the [natural numbers](/Natural_number). This is called the \( n \)-th **functional power** of \( f \).

If \( f \) is a [linear transformation](/Linear_transformation), then \( f^n \) is the \( n \)-th [matrix power](/Matrix_power) of the [matrix](/Matrix_(mathematics)) representing \( f \).

If \( f \) is a [permutation](/Permutation) of a set \( X \), then \( f^n \) is the \( n \)-th power of \( f \) as a permutation.

If \( f \) is a [function from a set to itself](/Function_(mathematics)), then \( f^n \) is the \( n \)-th [iterate](/Iterated_function) of \( f \).

## Composition of relations

The composition of functions is a special case of the composition of [relations](/Relation_(mathematics)). Given two [binary relations](/Binary_relation) \( R \) and \( S \), the composition \( S \circ R \) is defined as the set of all pairs \( (x, z) \) such that there exists a \( y \) with \( (x, y) \in R \) and \( (y, z) \in S \).

If \( R \) and \( S \) are functions, then \( S \circ R \) is the composition of \( R \) and \( S \) as functions.

## Composition of maps

The composition of functions is also a special case of the composition of [maps](/Function_(mathematics)). Given two [maps](/Function_(mathematics)) \( f \colon X \to Y \) and \( g \colon Y \to Z \), the composition \( g \circ f \colon X \to Z \) is defined by \( (g \circ f)(x) = g(f(x)) \) for all \( x \) in \( X \).

## Applications

The composition of functions is used in many areas of mathematics, including [calculus](/Calculus), [linear algebra](/Linear_algebra), and [abstract algebra](/Abstract_algebra). In calculus, the [chain rule](/Chain_rule) is a formula for the [derivative](/Derivative) of the composition of two functions. In linear algebra, the composition of linear transformations is used to define the [product of matrices](/Matrix_multiplication). In abstract algebra, the composition of functions is used to define the [composition of homomorphisms](/Homomorphism).

